\end{picture}
\end{eqnarray}
where tilde refers to the second pair of lines.
Propagator of the second type is a similar braid combined with the additional "regrouping operation"

\begin{eqnarray}
\begin{picture}(300,42)(-130,-22)

\put(-10,-12.5){\line(1,0){130}}
\put(-10,-7.5){\line(1,0){40}}
\put(-10,7.5){\line(1,0){40}}
\put(-10,12.5){\line(1,0){130}}

\qbezier(30,7.5)(40,7.5)(50,5)
\qbezier(50,5)(60,2.5)(70,2.5)

\qbezier(30,-7.5)(40,-7.5)(50,-5)
\qbezier(50,-5)(60,-2.5)(70,-2.5)

\put(70,2.5){\line(1,0){40}}
\put(70,-2.5){\line(1,0){40}}

\put(20,20){\line(1,0){70}}
\put(20,-20){\line(1,0){70}}
\put(20,20){\line(0,-1){40}}
\put(90,20){\line(0,-1){40}}

\put(-20,16){\mbox{$A$}}
\put(-20,-21){\mbox{$B$}}
\put(115,-2){\mbox{$C$}}
\put(120,16){\mbox{$D$}}
\put(120,-21){\mbox{$D$}}

\put(-100,-2){\mbox{$S_{AB|CD}:$}}
\end{picture}
\label{regroup}
\end{eqnarray}
where $D$ refers to the {\it pair} of strands.

It is now natural to impose a requirement that the rank-(2,2) tensor ${\cal K}$ is actually made from
the rank-(1,1) tensor $K$ by conjugation with the same "orthogonal" rank-(2,2)
regrouping tensor ${\cal S}$:
\begin{eqnarray}
{\cal K}_{AB|CD}^{\pm} =
\sum_{E,F,G} {\cal S}_{AB|EG}K^{\pm}_{EF}{\cal S}_{CD|FG} {\nonumber} \\
\sum_{E,G} {\cal S}_{AB|EG} {\cal S}_{CD|EG} = \delta_{AC}\delta_{BD}
\end{eqnarray}
Note that the first formula makes a difference between the third and forth indices of ${\cal S}$.
Also note that ${\cal S}$ does not commute with the $K$-tensors,
therefore it now matters, where the reordering operation is placed in the definition
of the propagator: our convention is to put it at the right end.

\bigskip

A motivation for the above definitions comes from unification \cite{mmmrs} of the modern
(Tanaka-Krein) version \cite{MMMkn2,RTmod} of the Reshetikhin-Turaev (RT) formalism \cite{RT}
with the conformal block calculus of \cite{inds,newinds,gmmms,mmms}.
The former provides the idea of tensor calculus, while the latter is
a concrete suggestion for the definition of caps and fingers.
Originally, the rank-2 tensors $K$ are quantum ${\cal R}$-matrices lifted to the
space of intertwining operators, while ${\cal S}$ are quantum Racah matrices
($6j$-symbols) acting at the same space.
As further noted in \cite{MMfam}, after rank-2 tensors are defined for {\it fingers},
they can be used in the role of $K$ instead of original ${\cal R}$-matrices;
then, different fingers can be inserted into different crossings of the braid.
For ${\cal R}$-matrices $K$ is further reduced to
\begin{eqnarray}
K_{AC}^\pm = T_A^{\pm 1}\delta_{AC},
\label{2red1}
\end{eqnarray}

\subsection{Knot polynomials for non-oriented double-fat (arborescent) knots
\label{nonorpols}}

If one wants to define a knot polynomial in a self-conjugate representation $R$ of Lie algebra ${\cal G}$,
the role of indices $A$ is played by irreducible representations in the tensor square
$R^{\otimes 2}$, and the eigenvalue $K_{AC}$ in (\ref{2red1}) is
\begin{eqnarray}
T_A = \pm q^{\varkappa_A}
\label{evR}
\end{eqnarray}
where $\varkappa_A$ is the eigenvalue of the second Casimir operator
(i.e. of the cut-and-join operator $\hat W_2$ of \cite{MMN1})
and the sign in (\ref{evR}) depends on whether $A$ belongs to the symmetric or antisymmetric squares
${\cal S}^2R$ or $\Lambda^2R$ respectively.

Actually, the decomposition is
\begin{eqnarray}
R^{\otimes 2} =
\oplus_{X} \ W_{X}\otimes X
\label{decoR2}
\end{eqnarray}
where $X$ are irreducible representations, and dimensions of the vector spaces $W_X$
are their multiplicities.
The index $A$ consists of two pieces: $A=(X,\alpha)$, where $\alpha$ labels
elements of some basis in $W_X$.

Now comes the crucial simplification in the theory of {\it arborescent} knots:
{\bf fingers are diagonal in $X$},
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{(X,\alpha)(Y,\beta)} = \delta_{XY} F_X^{\alpha\beta}
\end{eqnarray}
The reason for this is that  attaching a cup to the 4-strand braid
picks up a singlet representation $\emptyset$ out of $R^{\otimes 4}$, and
\begin{eqnarray}
\emptyset \in X\otimes Y \ \ \ \Longrightarrow \ \ \  Y=X
\end{eqnarray}


Generic 4-strand braid is labeled  by a sequence of integers
$(l_1,m_1,n_1|l_2,m_2,n_2|\ldots |l_k,m_k,n_k)$ and we define associated finger as
\begin{eqnarray}
F_X^{(l_1,m_1,n_1| \ldots |l_k,m_k,n_k)}  =
\frac{1}{S_{ X\emptyset}} \sum_{X_1,\ldots, Y_k}
T_X^{l_1}\underbrace{S_{XY_1}T_{Y_1}^{m_1}  S^\dagger_{Y_1X_1}}_{{\cal T}^{m_1}_{XX_1}}  \tilde T_{X_1}^{n_1}
\ \  \ldots \ \
T_{X_{k-1}}^{l_k}\underbrace{S_{X_{k-1}Y_k}T_{Y_k}^{m_k}  S^\dagger_{Y_kX_k}}_{{\cal T}^{m_k}_{X_{k-1}X_k}}
  \tilde T_{X_k}^{n_k}\  \P S_{ X_{K}\emptyset}
 \label{finger}
\end{eqnarray}
All $T$ and $S$ here are still matrices in the Greek indices,
with the only exception of
\begin{eqnarray}
S_{(X,\alpha),(X,\beta)|\emptyset,\emptyset} = \delta_{\alpha\beta} S_{X\emptyset}
\end{eqnarray}
which is proportional to the unit matrix.
Contraction of the Greek indices at the cap is denoted in above formula by $\P$.
Finally, $\tilde T$ stands for $T$ with the transposed Greek indices:
this operation can be non-trivial if one does not care about choosing some special
bases in the intertwiner spaces $W_X$.
In $S^\dagger$ both Latin and pairs of Greek indices are permuted.

\bigskip

In general, the propagator can be in non-trivial representation $Q\in R^{\otimes 4}$,
then one needs to know many Racah/mixing matrices $S^{(Q)}$ instead of a single $S=S^{(\emptyset)}$
which appeared in (\ref{finger}).
However, if the entire Feynman diagram is {\it tree}, i.e. the knot is {\it arborescent},
then $Q=\emptyset$ in the propagators as well, and one gets essentially the same formula (\ref{finger}):
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{XY}^{(l_1,m_1,n_1| \ldots |l_k,m_k,n_k)}  =
\frac{1}{S_{X \emptyset }S_{Y\emptyset}} \sum_{X_1,\ldots, Y_k}
T_X^{l_1}\underbrace{S_{XY_1}T_{Y_1}^{m_1}  S^\dagger_{Y_1X_1}}_{{\cal T}^{m_1}_{XX_1}} \tilde T_{X_1}^{n_1}
\ \  \ldots \ \
T_{X_{k-1}}^{l_k}\underbrace{S_{X_{k-1}Y_k}T_{Y_k}^{m_k}S^\dagger_{Y_kX_k }}_{{\cal T}^{m_k}_{X_{k-1}X_k}}
  \tilde T_{X_k}^{n_k}\ S_{X_kY}
 \label{prop}
\end{eqnarray}
We denote it $P$ instead of $\Pi$ in order to emphasize that it can be used only in {\it trees},
and it is a (1,1)-tensor in $X,Y$, while is still a (2,2)-tensor in the Greek indices.
An additional $S$ at the right end of the propagator appears if one wishes a regrouping.

If the normalization factors $S_{X\emptyset}$ are put in denominators,
as we did in (\ref{finger}) and (\ref{prop}), then at the vertices (\ref{vert}) of the {\it tree}
Feynman diagrams we simply convert the Greek (multiplicity) indices and sum over a single representation
index $X$ with the weight $d_X=S_{\emptyset X}^2 = S_{X\emptyset}^2$, which is just the
quantum dimension of representation $X$ independently of valence of the diagram.
If normalization factors are omitted from (\ref{finger}) and (\ref{prop}), then
the vertex of valence $n$ includes a weight $S_{\emptyset X}^{2-n}$ in the sum over $X$.

The last ingredient is the common factor $d_R$ or $d_R^2$ in the case of reduced or non-reduced
knot polynomials respectively. At least one factor is needed to make the entire expression
a polynomial.


\bigskip

Putting things together, the arborescent knot described by the {\it tree} Feynman fat diagram
(cf. \cite{Caudron})

